While preparing for a conference presentation on my Master's thesis project, I wondered if there was a better way to visually represent part of my data so that my audience would better understand the geographical spread of my data and what my data means spatially.

This section of my thesis involved surveying two transects composed of several segments going across a mudflat where each segment would be characterized based on what habitat was available within it and counting the number of individual snails residing in each section on six separate occasions. The segments were marked by stakes, and the latitude and longitude of each stake was recorded.

My goals for visualizing this data were firstly, to show the spatial spread of these segments on a map and secondly, to show the counts visually. To accomplish these two goals, I turned to use the Python package folium.

I then initialized the folium map and using a for loop, added the position of each stake for both transects onto the folium map as a CircleMarker to a folium FeatureGroup. Using CircleMarker also allowed me to make each stake on the map interactive so that when you press the stake's CircleMarker, a box would pop-up with the description of the preceding section. Adding the CircleMarker's to a FeatureGroup allows me, later on, to create layers on my map that could be turned on and off. Thus, allowing the flexibility for viewers to visualize different parts of my data easily.

In [5]:
# Initialize folium map with tiles set to cartodbpositron for easy viewing
# and at specific latitude and longitude to easily view the study site
init_lat = 48.67515
init_long = -68.02918

mp = fo.Map(tiles='cartodbpositron', location=[init_lat, init_long], zoom_start=15)
In [6]:
# Create a FeatureGroup on our map that will contain all the stake CircleMarkers
stakesLayer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Stakes").add_to(mp)

# Add stake positions and pop-up tile saying the section description
for pt in transect_A.itertuples():
    fo.CircleMarker([pt.latitude, pt.longitude],
                    popup = fo.Popup('<strong>' "Section Description: <br>" + str(pt.description_simple) + '</strong>'),
                    radius=2).add_to(stakesLayer)

for pt in transect_B.itertuples():
    fo.CircleMarker([pt.latitude, pt.longitude],
                    popup = fo.Popup('<strong>' "Section Description: <br>" + str(pt.description_simple) + '</strong>'),
                    radius=2).add_to(stakesLayer)

Now that I have the stakes geographically placed, viewers are given a better sense of where the data was collected. But could the rest of my data be shown effectively with scatterplots? Maybe to an extent. Below I use Python package seaborns to make a scatterplot for each transect showing the total number of individuals found in each section for each of the sample dates.

Although the two scatterplots above gives a good idea of how the totals fluctuate the section, I could more effectively show this information using folium. In the code below, I created two new FeatureGroup's to hold the line segments marking each section in the two transects. To accomplish this, I first had to zip the latitude and longitude of all the stakes in each transect respectively and use those to create folium ColorLine's. A ColorLine allows me to set a colour for the habitat descriptions of the sections, thus creating a colour code for the habitats. These lines are then added to our map to visually explain the variety of habitats in our transects.

In [11]:
# Zip latitude and longitude data for each transect respectively 
# and store in new column `tuples` 
transect_A['tuples'] = list(zip(transect_A['latitude'], transect_A['longitude']))
transect_B['tuples'] = list(zip(transect_B['latitude'], transect_B['longitude']))
In [12]:
list_colors = ['#ff8c00', '#00ffff', '#6495ed', '#228b22', '#9370db', '#ff0000', '#00ff7f', '#ffff00', '#ffc0cb']
In [13]:
A_descLayer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A Section Descriptions").add_to(mp)
B_descLayer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect B Section Descriptions").add_to(mp)

fo.ColorLine(
        positions = transect_A['tuples'], # tuple of coordinates 
        colors = transect_A['description_no'], # map each segment with the description 
        colormap = list_colors, # map each value with a color 
        weight = 3
        ).add_to(A_descLayer)

fo.ColorLine(
        positions = transect_B['tuples'], # tuple of coordinates 
        colors = transect_B['description_no'], # map each segment with the description 
        colormap = list_colors, # map each value with a color 
        weight = 3
        ).add_to(B_descLayer)

Finally, I wanted people to be able to directly visualize how the total number found in each section varied throughout the sections for each sample date separately.

In [15]:
# Function that takes as input a FeatureGroup name, transect_B/transect_A, and an int 
# and creates a new ColorLine that varies line weight based on the total number of 
# individuals found in each section for each sample date
def create_sample_dates(layer_name, transect, count):
    for index, row in transect.iterrows():
        if index == len(transect.index)-1:
            break
        else:
            df2 = transect.iloc[[index,index+1],:]
            fo.ColorLine(
                    positions = df2['tuples'], # tuple of coordinates 
                    colors = transect['description_no'], # map each segment with the description 
                    colormap = list_colors, # map each value with a color
                    weight = 0.5+(transect.iloc[index,count]/100)
                    ).add_to(layer_name)
In [16]:
# Create FeatureGroup's for each sample date for Transect A
A_mayLayer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A May 29 Totals").add_to(mp)
A_jun1Layer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A June 13 Totals").add_to(mp)
A_jun2Layer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A June 23 Totals").add_to(mp)
A_jul1Layer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A July 10 Totals").add_to(mp)
A_jul2Layer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A July 22 Totals").add_to(mp)
A_augLayer = fo.FeatureGroup(name="Transect A August 8 Totals").add_to(mp)

# A list of all Transect A's FeatureGroup's names
A_layerlist = [A_mayLayer, A_jun1Layer, A_jun2Layer, A_jul1Layer, A_jul2Layer, A_augLayer]

# Loop to create the ColorLine's for each sample date
count = 6
for item in A_layerlist:
    create_sample_dates(item, transect_A, count)
    count += 1

The final step was to add in the folium LayerControl which allows users of the map to choose which layers are viewable. As you may recall, I added the ColorLine's and CircleMarker's to layers throughout my code. Now viewers can control what they want to be able to see using the button in the top right corner of the map. A drop-down menu will appear given viewers the options for what data points they can see.

In [19]:
fo.LayerControl().add_to(mp)
mp
Out[19]:
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

In general, this single folium map not only packs in a lot of data into one convenient form but also allows it to be viewed spatially, which is key to ecological data such as this. This is a very useful way to visualize and present data in presentations and online. On the other hand, the LayerControl doesn't end up being very useful because interaction cannot be built into academic papers but overall, this was an excellent exercise in visualizing spatial data.
